<br>
Basically, there are 2 ways that Dual classing would work.<br>
<br>
1.  The first is 2nd ed method.  That is, when you decide to dual class, you can't use ANY of the powers you have in your original class until you get back to that level in your new class(actually its one level higher, but thats not really important).  So if your a level 60 rogue, and dualed into an SK, you would start at level 1, with no powers, and when you hit level 60, you would not only have the powers of a 60 SK, but you would suddenly get BACK all the powers of your 60 rogue.\<br>
<br>
2.  The second method is 3rd ed.  This is basically this, raising a level always takes exp reguardless of what class your raising it in, but you keep the powers you already had.  An example in D&amp;D would be this, it would take the same exp for a level 4 fighter to reach level 5 fighter as it would for a level 4 fighter to gain their 1st level as a rogue.  And then gaining the second level as a rogue would cost as much as getting 6th level.  And so on.  So in EQ if you were a level 60 rogue, and dual classed to SK, getting level 1 as an SK would take as much exp as level 61.  And level 2 as an SK would cost as much exp as getting to level 62.<br>
<br>
These methods both have their merits and such.<br>
<br>
The first method is probably better from a game balance perspective.  It forces the player to start playing from scratch at the low levels and getting all the way back up that they did the first time.  The downside is...this method really makes NO damn sense.  Why do I, because I start training as a shadowknight, suddenly COMPLETELY forget everything I learned as a rogue?  And why, when I get back to level 60, do I all of a sudden remember everything I had forgotten about being a rogue?<br>
<br>
The second method leads to alot more powerful character sooner, because they keep their old skills, and immediatly start adding new powers of the new class.  This is balanced by the fact that it takes ALOT of exp to gain levels and thus, their power increases alot slower.  But it also means the player doesn't have to start fighting newbie zone mobs and working their way back up. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#FF0000>- </font><a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bthesafehouse>The Safehouse</a><font color=#FF0000> - </font><a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion>Main Lounge</a> <font color=#FF0000> - </font><a href="http://www.thesafehouse.org">The Safehouse website</a><font color=#FF0000> - </font> <center><a href="http://www.guildboss.com"><img
